< Text>
I used animal Medical Center of MV for boarding a new rescue cat (Jackson) that needed multiple daily medications post-procedure.  The poor dear had an ulcerated cornea from a claw in the eye.  He had an ophthalmology procedure performed by the SoCal Veterinary Specialists (Dr Mar) and needed medicated eyedrops administered 3 times a day.
As Jackson's brand new caretaker, I was confronted with a scared, anxious cat that had been abandoned twice and did not like or trust people.  I was so stressed out that I couldn't give him his necessary post-procedure eye drops (he was NOT having it!) that I reached out to this local vet center for help.
The wonderful staff here at Animal Medical Center boarded him and had no problems giving him his prescribed eyedrops.  When I contacted them, Jill was very helpful and caring, and Sara & Morgan were outstanding staff members that radiated compassion and their love of animals.  These two wonderful ladies were professional and empathetic towards the tough times this poor animal had been subjected to.
I visited Jackson most days he stayed here (which was the most I've ever been at a vet) and their operations here are top notch - with animal welfare being a top priority.
This place and the staff members mentioned above are real gems.  They've earned my trust and I will be back.< /Text>

<Text>Not the worst, not the best.

I bought my 8-week old puppy and brought her in same day for the an overall exam under the pup plan. Mind you, I had previously called a week prior or so to make this appointment and confirmed that it wouldn't be a problem to do this exam and initial shots, etc. after driving 3 hours north from where we got her.

Upon arrival, Dr. Dhanoa said that we probably shouldn't give her the shots because of the drive... Okay, I live far away, so I asked we please do them. She was a big puppy so I doubted she'd get sick. And she was fine.

He also urged several times we get her back dew claws removed because the family we bought her from couldn't stomach the thought of cutting them off themselves. That's fine on both of their parts, but he made us feel bad about it like it was our choice. And since we have a shared yard with our neighbors with dogs, he said to absolutely not let her outside until she got all of her distemper shots plus a month on top of that....

Anyways, they said they would call me within 2 days for the fecal results but I didn't hear anything so I called on the third day. Not thinking anything of it (because silence is usually a good thing), they surprisingly told me that "she came back positive for a few things"... uh what? I asked to talk to the vet and they said he was very busy, probably wouldn't call back until tomorrow.

I am biting my fingernails hoping he will call and tell me what's up. I finally hear from him and he says she has roundworm and that she needs medication right away. This was at 4:30pm in the middle of the week, I work in Long Beach and I didn't get off for another hour. I had to zip down there and get it before 7pm. If it was so urgent, you'd think he would've actually called himself, you know, with some sort of sense of urgency. I asked if I could get dewormer for my cat, too, since I had no idea for the past few days (I even thought I had it at once point, they're super contagious) and they tried to say they really shouldn't but agreed to finally after I said that the doctor insisted I keep the puppy inside and had had accidents all over the house already.

A few months later, my pup was having digestive problems and I spent over $200 running tests that proved nothing. I thought it was bacterial from being in the ocean, but come to find out that the $65 I spent on an upgraded fecal test didn't even test for bacteria. Ended up fixing the problem by going to the local Pet Supply down the road who offered solutions the vet never did.

Long story short: Vet techs and front desk are very nice and helpful, but I found another vet.</Text>< Pics>

<GmapID>0x80dd31a0f95e5fbf:0x1274e79aa83e3c6d<//GmapID><username>Robin Brouwer</username>< Review>
We found the Tap House as we strolled 2nd St with some friends and decided to give them a try ... really glad we did! We started with fried pickles (when I saw them arrive with a tempura batter rather than cornmeal I was skeptical, but they were really good!) and an order of Monster Fries (topped with grilled onions, melted cheese, and a yummy sauce). The guys had a Mac & Cheese burger and a California Love burger ... both were a hit. The girls had the grilled chicken sandwich on sourdough (the name escapes me), and we both enjoyed it. The sandwiches were large enough that we (the girls) each took home half for lunch tomorrow. The Irish mules were also nicely made. Jacob took great care of us as well. No complaints here ... we look forward to coming back!</Review>

Edit: I have since received an apology and refund from the clinic. They were very polite and professional once they contacted me, so I have increased my review from one to three stars. However, I am still leaving my original review below because this series of events still happened. (In the end, it took about a month to receive a response.)

***********

I needed a health certificate for international travel for my cat and went here because they have one of the few "USDA certified" vets in the area. I paid $150 and waited two hours for Dr. Pawar to fill out the necessary paperwork to bring to the LA Animal Import Center so that I could take my cat when I flew internationally the next week. During our brief phone discussion, Dr. Pawar referred to the cat by the wrong sex, but I assumed it was such standard paperwork that a full exam was not necessary. I had brought with me the correct form for them to fill out and offered to give it to the vet, but an assistant assured me they had the paperwork on file.

I had to set a whole day aside and find someone to drive me to LA to have the paperwork processed at the LA Animal Import Center, only to receive a phone call an hour and a half after I dropped it off telling me that the vet had filled out completely the wrong form and I would have no other option than to get my cat examined by a different USDA certified vet or drive 60 miles back to Riverside to have Dr. Pawar fill out the correct paperwork and then drive 60 miles BACK for them to process it at the USDA office. I had no other choice but to drive back to Riverside immediately, as my flight was the very next day. Upon arriving at the vet's office and giving them the correct paperwork along with the AIC's instructions on exactly how to fill it out, only a few minutes later an assistant came out and told me she had "already found the form online and started filling it out" before I arrived. She then tried to give me a completed form in Hungarian. I pointed out to her that this was not the correct language, as the form I had brought with me was in Croatian.  She still refused to believe me until I took the (untouched) correct form out of the envelope and compared them side by side in front of her. She finally accepted it and went back inside to fill out the correct paperwork. By the time it was actually correctly filled out and signed, it was too late in the day for me to return to the LA AIC office that day, so I ended up having to take an expensive and unnecessary detour on my way to the airport the next morning to have them approve the paperwork first thing. If they had not been understanding of the extraordinary circumstances and put a rush order on approving it, I would have missed my $900 flight.</Text>

<user_id>103739323999799818551<//user_id><Time>1593787936561<//Time>< text>
Been here a few times over the years and come back because they have a nice big space that is big for groups. Beer is OK, not my favorite but it is serviceable. Came in a few weeks ago and all staff were masked up and there were signs on the doors about their procedures. Did not see any table get washed down though in between parties and no other group except ours was wearing masks when they weren't seating at their tables. I didn't see the bathrooms cleaned or sanitized while we were visiting either. Unless their staff follows through with the cleaning procedures and you see them wash and sanitize your table, I'd assume it hasn't been done. Probably best to stay away for the time being.<//text>

< review>
Cool, chill brewery. Soo far one of the best I've been to. I like the fact they have tv's, so you catch a game or any other shows. They have someone catering the food, the day I went they had brick oven baked pizza. Super delicious, and the variety of beers is great. My favorites were muffin top and Hugh Heff-weizen (hope I spelled it right), full flavored, full bodied brews. The place is spacious, has games and various places to sit in. They also have an outside patio for those nice summer nights. The staff is nice and very helpful, they make you feel welcomed. They also have a live band on the weekends. Give it a try. Communal sitting is a nice touch as well. Cheers!</review>

< review>
This is one of our favorite brew pubs in the area. The space is huge worth plenty of seating. They have an outdoor seating area as well. They have a great variety of beers on tap from sours and IPA's to brown ales and porters. You can bring in your own food or have it delivered. The music is loud enough to hear but not so loud that you need to shout. All in all a great hang-out spot.  The only down side is the limited parking.< /review>

The Brewery has outdoor live music on Sat evenings from 7-10 pm. The outdoor area also has a rotation of outdoor food vendors. The inside area is large and has a separate area inside for a private parties if you reserve ahead of time with TVs. This venue is located in an industrial building adjacent to La Verne/Claremont borders. They only serve their rotation of beers: some are fruity, sour or stouty. Try a flight of five tasting before you commit to a favorite brew.<//Review>

<user>118177160829918064966<//user>< response>
None< /response>
< text>
Love this spot. Only one issue... The beer is extremely soft and by that I mean it lacks in carbonation or is practically flat. Now please feel free to correct me if I'm wrong (I'm ok with knowledge) but... A properly carbonated beer will dance on your tounge upon being drank. Almost a tingling sensation..When held up to the light you should be able to see co2 bubbles clinging to the glass as well as traveling up. And when held up to your ear you should be able to hear the sound of effervescence ... I don't get that from these beers. Now at at first I tried the brown and porter and thought maybe this is kinda a style of beer thing . Cause English and British style beers are kinda soft , but as I've tried the other beers. It was the same issue, exept with the (super tatsy)apricot gose . Which I imagine has been sitting there long enough that the Co2 sitting on it has carbonated it over time. I like the beers (except p town porter)..they're tasty and on point. But whould be soooo much more enjoyable if a lil more Co2 came in contact with them.  If y'all need help hand jamming kegs ..Im down... But please more carbonation please...with a cherry on top.<//text>

<Review>I have a few things to share about the place and the service, less about the food. The most important one - THE TIP IS INCLUDED IN THE BILL!

The good
* The freshly squeezed juices are soooo good! Very refreshing, although not cheap (~$6-7 for a medium sized glass)
* The food is fresh and good - Chocolate chip pancakes were delicious!

The bad
* PSA! The tip is already included when you get the check! - They never mentioned that, and I found out about it a few hours too late. I know it's my fault as you should scan the bill and verify, but that usually happens when there is a big party - We were four people, and no one mentioned anything about it. Really annoying and makes you feel cheated.
* The place is tiny but we were ready for that and joined the queue from home via Yelp. When we came, we were the third party in line (total of four people). With all that, we've waited over 50 minutes to be seated. Not sure if we got unlucky, but this something you need to take into consideration
* Brunch - The potatoes were good, a bit too salty, the eggs were great, but no salt or pepper at all.  Kind of weird.

Due to the issue with the tip, while the place is nice, I feel like it is not entirely honest and I won't be coming back.</Review>< pics>

<Review>Ate the crazy Moco (pork katsu, rice, gravy, 2 eggs sunny side up), which is a very filling and delicious way to start your day. The atmosphere is a bit loud due to the small space, but the service is fairly fast and the large glass walls make the space feel larger. There are both tables and counter seats which filled up around noon today. When we arrived at 1130,  we did not wait for a table (4 top).

If you're looking for a good, solid breakfast beyond your standard eggs, bacon, and toast, I recommend coming here. If it's busy, be prepared to wait.</Review><pics>None<//pics>< Response>

< UserId.>
111373398408579758296< /UserId.>
< username>
Roland Bellerud</username>
< Time>
1536005258955< /Time>
< Rating>
4< /Rating>
< Text>
Wait: As there are very few brunch spots around the Inner Richmond, this place tends to have a 20-30 min wait. They do have the Yelp reservation system though, so you can reserve your spot in line ahead of time without having to actually wait outside.

Ambiance: The place is pretty small, but has a cozy feel. Even though it's usually busy, service is pretty fast and staff is friendly and attentive.

Food: I had the Crazy Moco with a side of bacon. The pork katsu was slightly dry, but the crust was super crispy. The gravy was very rich and had a nice little kick (though I could use a little more). The bacon was nice and thick, but still crispy. My companion had the crab Benedict. The eggs were poached well and the hollandaise was nice and creamy. The crab wasn't too sweet, but was still good.

Price: The portions are quite big here, but the price seemed a bit too high for what you are getting. The Benedict dish ended up being around $30.< /Text>

<user_id>102145669473009446719<//user_id><Name>Sonia S.< /Name>< date>
1490283677807< /date>
<Rate>5</Rate>< review>
I have rented a storage unit from a different facility before, and comparing them to Big E there is no comparison. Their pricing and specials are very competitive and reasonable. The site is clean, I did not see any rodents or bugs in my storage unit or on the property all together. They have great security and know what is going on at all times so I felt more at ease storing my entire home here in their storage facility. Access going in and out of the facility is very easy, I never once had a problem getting in or out or my pin not working. Ashley the on site manager is extremely helpful, and flexible with your needs. She can answer any question you have and is very eager and willing to help you in any way. I particularly asked about rats getting into the unit and she offered to put some type of a packet in my unit to help ensure that did not happen. She is very friendly and easy to talk to. Unlike my past experience at the last storage place I rented from the employees were on their personal phones while assisting me and just plain rude. I did not get any of that while renting from BIG E! Her assistant in the office was also very friendly and helpful, it's good to know that not only the manager but all other employees are knowledgeable and eager to help you.  From my initial phone call to ask about their specials and pricing to my move out I was very pleased with BIG E and how they make sure customer service is their main priority!. I would HIGHLY recommend them! Especially since I've rented from a couple other storage facilities in the Stockton area, and can vouch for BIG E.  Give them a call! They're the BEST in the Stockton area, you will not be disappointed!<//review>
